l writing into the postphonetic, ideographic system of digital media, which not only altered the threshold of sense and nonsense in communication processes but also compelled a new understanding of human-machine interplay at the level of the unconscious. Ranging across information theory, cybernetics, modernism, literary theory, neurotic machines, and psychoanalysis, The Freudian Robot rewrites the history of digital media and the literary theory of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aComputer science. 0aConscious automataxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aCyberneticsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aRoboticsxHuman factors. 0aRoboticsxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aScience. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aidentity, digital, media, freud, unconscious, alphabetical writing, psychoanalysis, word-association, literary theory, cybernetics, robotics, conscious automata, artificial intelligence, grammatology, joyce, finnegans wake, bell labs, lacan, poe, purloined letter, uncanny valley, minsky, nonfiction, philosophy, computer science, technology, literature, culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226486840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226486840/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles